@node CtrlCode "Control codes"
                                   Ctrl Codes
                                  ============

              Put these ctrl codes in any text string or textfile.
                        Displaycodes ARE case sensitive!

         All displaycodes are parsed thru sprintf(), that means you can
                    do string justifications etc very easy.

           %d - Output an integer with base 10 (standard decimal)
           %x - Output an integer with base 16, small letters (hex)
           %X - Output an integer with base 16, capital letters (hex)
           %o - Output an integer with base 8 (octal)
           %s - Output a string
           %% - Output an %

      %8d  - Integer, 8 characters wide, right justified
      %-8d - Integer, 8 characters wide, left justified
      %08d - Integer, 8 characters wide, right justified padded with zeros

           Example: Hello ~ua%s~, you have uploaded $~uk%08x~ bytes!
    Could result: Hello Niclas Emdelius, you have uploaded $002a5e73 bytes!


    It's important that you don't use %s instead of %d when a number should
                                 be displayed!

         @{"User codes" Link User}@{"System codes" Link System}@{"Action codes" Link Action}@{"Message codes" Link Msg}@{"File codes" Link File}

@endnode
@node User "User codes:"

~ua%s~  Username
~ub%s~  City
~uc%d~  Access level
~ud%s~  Adress
~ue%s~  handle
~uf%s~  Password
~ug%s~  Zip code
~uh%s~  Tele
~ui%d~  Calls
~uj%d~  Carrier lost (times)
~uk%d~  Bytes uploaded
~ul%d~  Bytes downloaded
~um%d~  Files uploaded
~un%d~  Files downloaded
~uo%d~  Messages written
~up%d~  Graphics mode
~uqX~   Last read message in area X (0=current area)
~ur%d~  Screen Length
~us%d~  Time/Day
~ut%d~  Time/Call
~uu%d~  Minutes used
~uU%d~  Minutes remaining
~uv%d~  Calls/day
~uw%d~  Calls today
~ux%d~  File ratio
~uy%d~  Byte ratio
~uz%d~  Current MsgArea nr
~uZ%d~  Current Filearea nr
~uX%d~  Files available before upload
~uY%d~  Bytes available before upload
~uT%d~  Character translation
~uB%d~  Year of birth (00-99)
~uM%d~  Month of birth (1-12)
~uD%d~  Day of birth (1-31)
~uN%d~  Usernumber
~uO%d~  Protocol number
~uP%s~  Protocol name
~uA%d~  Computer number
~uC%s~  Computer name
~uF%s~  First name
~uL%s~  Last name

@endnode
@node System "System codes:"

~saX~   Name of msgarea X (0=current)
~sbX~   Msglow in msgarea X (0=current)
~scX~   MsgHigh in msgarea X (0=current)
~sdX~   Nr of messages in msgarea X (0=current)
~seX~   Name of filearea X (0=current)
~sf%s~  Name of last user online
~sl%d~  Current Rcn-node
~ss%d~  Uploadspace available in current filearea (in kb)
~sh%d~  Current time - hour
~sm%d~  Current time - minute
~st%d~  Current time - second
~sD%d~  Current date - day
~sM%d~  Current date - month (1-12)
~sY%d~  Current date - year (0-99)
~sXS~   Expertmode-status. Outputs the string S if expertmode enabled.
~sxS~   Expertmode-status. Outputs the string S if expertmode disabled.

@endnode
@node Action "Action codes:"

~aa~    Hangup user
~acX~   Wait until user press the X key, where X is the ASCII vaule
        of that key. (0=any key, 13=return)
~adX~   Disable output for accesslevels <X (~ad0~ to turn it on again)
~afX~   Send a '*' if user have unread messages in area X
~agX~   Pause X tenths of a second
~ah~    Flash local screens (using DisplayBeep(0L))
~ai~    Clear screen (Use!!!)
~ajN~   Display textfile N (Do not use too recursive!)
~aFX~   Send a '+' if a user has tagged filearea X (0 = current)
~aMX~   Send a '+' if a user has tagged msgarea X (0 = current)
~aq%s~  Displays a quote selected from reccoon:quotes.bbs.

/*
~ay~    Disable CTRL-C
~az~    Enable CTRL-C again
*/

@endnode
@node Msg "Message codes:"

~ma%d~  Message number
~mt%s~  Message addressed to
~mf%s~  Message addressed from
~ms%s~  Message subject
~my%d~  Date, year
~mm%d~  Date, month (digit)
~mM%s~  Date, month (verbal)
~md%d~  Date, day
~mq%d~  Time, hour
~mu%d~  Time, minute
~mv%d~  Time, second
~mz%d~  Destination zone (netmails only)
~me%d~  Destination net
~mn%d~  Destination node
~mp%d~  Destination point
~moS~   Destination node-address (complete) if NetMail! (Where S is a string)
        Example: ~mo on %d:%d/%d.%d~ <= will output " on 2:201/414.0" if the
        message was a netmail to 2:201/414.0
~mZ%d~  Origin zone
~mE%d~  Origin net
~mN%d~  Origin node
~mP%d~  Origin point
~mOS~   Origin node-address (complete) if NetMail! Look at the ~mo~ code!
~mr%d~  Read-By count
~mbS~   Received flag    (Where S is a string. Example: ~mb<Received>~ )
~mkS~   Private flag     (Where S is a string.)
~mgS~   Fileattach flag  (Where S...)
~mGS~   Negative Fileattach flag (i.e if not fileattach)
~mhS~   Forwarded flag
~miS~   Mailproced flag
~mjS~   Direct-netmail flag
~mcS~   Crash-netmail flag
~mlS~   To-All flag
~mw%d~  Min-Access
~mWS~   Minaccess, flag format (ex: ~mw<MinAccess %d>~)

@endnode
@node File "File codes:"

~fn%d~  File number
~fN%s~  Filename (Normal)
~fZ%s~  Filename (BIG chars only)
~fz%s~  Filename (small chars only)
~fs%d~  Filesize (in kB)
~fS%s~  Filesize (Adjusting to either MB or kB with one decimal)
~fE%s~  Unit (kB/MB) for ~fS%s~
~fe%d~  Filesize in bytes
~fd%d~  Day when the file was uploaded
~fm%d~  Month when the file was uploaded
~fM%s~  Month (with 3 letters) when the file was uploaded
~fy%d~  Year when the file was uploaded
~fh%d~  Hour when the file was uploaded
~fu%d~  Minute when the file was uploaded
~fv%d~  Second when the file was uploaded
~fU%s~  Name of the uploader
~fB%s~  First line of the description
~fb%s~  Second line of the description
~ft%s~  Time for download of this file.
~fD%d~  Number of downloads

@endnode

@node Files "Files shown"

All textfiles must be located in your textfile directory set in Config.
The following extensions are supported:

        .TXT    - Graphic mode 0
        .GR1    - Graphic mode 1
        .GR2    - Graphic mode 2 etc..

A certain file can be shown for each user, and each access level. The
filename format is like this: <FileName>[_level]|[-usernum].<GRX|TXT>

      Examples:
                Logon-5.GR1     is shown to user #5 if he has graphics
                                mode 1 on.
                Logon_10.GR2    is shown to all level 10 users with
                                graphics mode 2.
                Logon_10.TXT    is shown to all level 10 users with
                                graphics mode 0, or if there is no
                                Logon_10.GRx file.
                Logon.TXT       Is shown to all users that doesnt match any
                                other textfile.

Banner.TXT      - Shown before an user enters his name.
BadPW.TXT       - Shown if an user fail to enter correct PW 3 times.
LockedOut.TXT   - Shown when a locked out user tries to logon.
Logon.TXT       - Shown when an user has loged on.
News.TXT        - Shown right after Logon.TXT
NewUser.TXT     - Shown when a new user is signing in
CallSysop.TXT   - Shown when user calls sysop. (fill it with BELLs!)
MsgListX.TXT    - Messarearea listing for SIG X
FileListX.TXT   - Filearea listing for SIG X
NoMail.TXT      - Shown when an user dont have any waiting messages.
Birthday.TXT    - Shown when a user is having his birthday
Security.TXT    - Shown when the user is prompted for a securitycheck

@endnode
@node Quest "Quest files"

Questfiles must always have the extension .Quest. When a new user is signing
in, he'll be questioned the questions in the file named Reccoon:NewUser.Quest.
Answers to questions will be put in files with the extension .Answer.
Different questions for different graphicsmodes are supported. Simply put
-graphicsmode before the .Quest extension.

The .Quest fileformat is like this:
    text text text ###<MODE>
    text text text
    ###<MODE>

Different modes:
     0 - Show question and then wait for user input. User DONT have to answer
         this question.
     1 - Show question and then wait for user input. User HAVE to answer the
         question.
     2 - Show question, but don't wait for input. Not very useful, but
         anyway...
     3 - Show question and prompt user for return-press.

Example NewUser-0.Quest:

     Street address (Three lines)
     ###1
     ###0
     ###0
     Where did you hear about this BBS?
     ###1
     What is the answer of life, the universe and everything? ###0
     What is your favourite colour?
     ###0

@endnode
@node Arexx "Arexx control"

Reccoon and ReccControl supports a number of arexxcommands. All at your
disposal.

@{"Reccoon" Link RXRcn}
@{"ReccControl" Link RXRcnCtrl}

@endnode

@node RXRcn "Reccoon's arexx commands"

ARexx commands can be sent to Rcn at anytime, but they won't be processed
until an ongoing download or upload is completed. The ARexx ports are
named ReccRexxY where Y is the line-number. ARexx-commands are not case-
sensitive.

IF YOU MISS SOMETHING, LET ME KNOW!!! It's VERY easy for me to add an ARexx
command!!! And PLEASE report bugs in the existing commands as well! (I'm not
an heavy ARexx user, as you might have noticed)

NOTE! The way you address rcn arexx command, might be a bit diffrent from
what you are used to, so here is a quick demo of how to obtain a string from
a user (Ofcourse, the number infrontof each line shouldn't be entered):

--- 8< ---
1 /* A little arexx demo */
2 OPTIONS RESULTS
3 ADDRESS "ReccRexx0"
4 'GetString 10'
5 str = result
6 'SendString You entered: 'str
7 EXIT
--- 8< ---

A quick explaination:

1: A remark. If it isn't the first line, the Arexx script will fail.
2: Tell arexx to give us the result from the commands we execute
3: We want to address node 0, so, ReccRexx0 = Node 0
4: Here's the strange part ;) You should ALWAYS put the rcnarexx command
   in '' or it _WILL_NOT_WORK_
5: This command returns the string, and puts it in the RESULT variable.
6: Now we send it back to the user, and again, we use '' to make it work.
7: Tells arexx that the script is at its end.

Oki, I hope you understood the example, anyway, here are the commands:


 Command        Args             Description
--------------+----------------+--------------------------------------------
SendString    |'string'        | Send a textline to the user. Returns 5 if
              |                |  the string was aborted with Ctrl-C.
Skriv         |'string'        | Send a textline to the local console only.
ShowFile      |'file'          | Displays a textfile for the user. Path and
              |                |  extensions are added. Returns 5 if the
              |                |  textfile was aborted with Ctrl-C.
RawSendString |'string'        | Works as SendSTring, except it doesn't
              |                |  process displaycodes.
Hangup        | none           | Drop the carrier. End your ARexx script
              |                |  after this!
Logoff        | none           | Log off user
GetString     | len            | Get input from from user.
Prompt        |'string'        | Prompt user for input.
GetUser       | 1              | Returns username
              | 2              |         accesslevel
              | 3              |         graphicsmode
              | 4              |         bytes UL
              | 5              |         bytes DL
              | 6              |         files UL
              | 7              |         files DL
              | 8              |         calls
Carrier       | none           | Get carrier state. Returns 5 if carrier
              |                |  lost.
ShutDown      | none           | Shutdown this Rcn-line
AddTime       | minutes        | Adds time to the user. Returns the number
              |                |  of minutes remaining.
Iconify       | none           | Iconify this Rcn-line.
Popup         | none           | Deiconify this Rcn-line if iconified.
DosMarkFile   | filename       | Allowes you to mark files anywhere on the
              |                |  disk.
MenuCommand   | CMD args       | Execute a menu-command. The first argument
              |                |  is the command-NUMBER, and the second are
              |                |  optional arguments.
              |                |  Look in Include/Reccoon/Menu.h for
              |                |  commandnumbers!
              |                |  Example: MenuCommand 21 Whom it may concern
ContinueBBS   | none           | Let the BBS continue. Use this when you're
              |                |  ending an ARexx-script started with the
              |                |  ARexx-menucommand.
CookString    |'string'        | Converts displaycodes to a string that
              |                |  you can use in your program. Very powerful.
Print         |'string'        | Prints 'string' w/linefeed
OutText       |'string'        | Prints 'string' w/o linefeed
NewLine       | none           | Sends a linefeed
BBSIdentify   | BBS            | Returns the name of the BBS software
              | USER           | Returns current user's name in quotes,
              |                |  location in quotes, and level.
              | TERM           | Returns user's termsettings as pagewith,
              |                |  pageheight, baud, line#
              | ANSI           | Returns 1 if ANSI-graphics is used.
DisplayFile   |'filename'      | Displays any textfile, located anywhere on
              |                |  the harddrive.
CLS           | none           | Clears screen.
KickOff       | none           | Same as Logoff.
CheckAbort    | none           | Returns 1 if user hits ctrl-c.
SysopLog      | 'string'       | Writes 'string' to log. (level2)
InputWaiting  | none           | Checks for userinput waiting, returns 1 if
              |                |  there is, else returns 0.
MayGetChar    |'string'        | Prompts user for a character and returns
              |                |  immediately. If a character was waiting
              |                |  it's returned, otherwise NOCHAR is
              |                |  returned.
GetChar       |'string'        | Command to get a character via hotkey,
              |                |  displays 'string' as prompt.
GetLine       | LEN NORMAL 's' | Displayes 's' as a prompt, allows user to
              |                |  enter a string of LEN characters long,
              |                |  returns the string entered.
              | LEN HIDE 'str' | Same as above, but hides users input.
              | YESNO 'str'    | Displays 'str' with a (Y/n) hotkey. Returns
              |                |  Y or N, defaults to Y.
              | NOYES 'str'    | Displays 'str' with a (y/N) hotkey. Returns
              |                |  Y or N, defaults to N.
GetUserVar    | NAME           | Returns user's name
              | PASSWORD       |    "      "    password
              | LOCATION       |    "      "    location
              | VOICETELEPHONE |
              | FILERATIO      |
              | BYTERATIO      |
              | CALLSTODAY     |
              | CALLLIMITPERDAY|
              | MENUSET        |
              | PRIVILEGE      |
              | TIMELIMIT      |
              | TIMEREMAINING  |
              | DOWNLOADS      |
              | UPLOADS        |
              | CALLS          |
              | MESSAGES       |
              | DOWNLOADBYTES  |
              | UPLOADBYTES    |
MESSAGE       |'string'        | Prints 'string' w/linefeed
MSG           |'string'        | Prints 'string' w/o linefeed
--------------+----------------+--------------------------------------------
@endnode
@node RXRcnCtrl "ReccControl's arexx commands"

ReccControl also got an Arexx-interface, using the same message-port
as doors and utilities do. It's named 'ReccControl-Port' and you can send
commands to it whenever you feel like it.

Ofcourse are some system-checking done before the command executes, so
you can't for instance shutdown ReccControl before it's unused.

(NOTE! Same rules for command usage applies here (See @{"Reccoon's" Link RXRcn} interface.))

 Command        Args             Description
--------------+----------------+---------------------------------------------
Hide          |                | Hide userinterface
Popup         |                | Show userinterface
Quit          |                | System shutdown
Save          |                | Save configuration
Flush         |                | Flush configuration from memory
Load          |                | Load configuration into memory
OpenScreen    |                | Open ReccControl's public screen
CloseScreen   |                | Close ReccControl's public screen
NODES         |                | Returns number of nodes in system
NODENR        | <nr>           | Returns the REAL line number of node <nr>
              |                | (See Arexx.man for more info)
WHOIS         | <nr>           | Returns the name of real line <nr>
--------------+----------------+---------------------------------------------
@endnode

@node menu "Menu-Commands"

Listing of available menucommands for use in both simple menus,
and advanced FPL-menus:

[] means optional argument
<> means required argument

Logoff [Textfile]          - Logoff user.

Log <String>               - Put a single line in the logfile.

Yell                       - Call for the Sysop.

LinkMenu <Menupage>        - Jump to another menupage. By using this in FPL-
                             scripts, you can easily mix standard menus with
                             menus written in FPL.

Execute                    - Startup a complete Remote-Shell. Passing an
                             argument to this function will start a dos-door
                             using fifo.device.

Previous                   - Jump to previous menupage. DON'T USE THIS IN FPL-
                             SCRIPTS!

PutBuff <String>           - Put a string into the input-buffer. Can be
                             useful!

DropBuff                   - Clear input-buffer.

UserList [Search]          - Show the userlist. If no argument is passed, the
                             user will be prompted for a searchstring, if the
                             argument ALL is passed, Rcn will display all
                             your users.

RunDoor [Filename]         - Run a Rcn-door or Doorlink-door.

Quest <Filename>           - Ask the user questions.

ShowMenu                   - Show current menu-textfile. No file is shown if
                             the user have expertmode selected.

GetReturn [Prompt]         - Prompt the user for a return-press.

ShowFile <Textfile>        - Show a textfile. Path and extension is appended.

ShowAnyFile <Textfile>     - Show a textfile, with full path

ShowNonstop <Textfile>     - Show a textfile, without pausing.

ShowAnyNonstop <Textfile>  - Show a textfile, with full path and without
                             pausing.

Echo <String>              - Send a string to the user.

Cls                        - Clear the screen.

ExpShowMenu                - Show current menu-textfile, no matter if the user
                             have extertmode on or off.

ParRunDoor <Filename>      - Run a Paragon-door program.

Password <Anything>        - Prompt user for password. If he failes, current
                             menu-key processing will be stopped.

SIG [Sig]                  - Set current menuSIG and fileSIG.

MsgArea [Area]             - Set current messagearea-number.

WriteMsg [To-name]         - Post a pessage in current area.

WaitingMail                - Check for waiting mail.

BackMsgArea                - Go to msgarea-1.

NextMsgArea                - Go to msgarea+1.

ReadForward [Start]        - Read messages forward.

ReadNew                    - Read new messages in current area.

ReadReverse [Start]        - Read messages backward.

ReadMarked                 - Read marked messages (not supported yet)

GlobalReadNew [Sig]        - Read all new in current or specified SIG.

SearchNodelist [String]    - Search the nodelist for a string.

ScanMsg                    - Scan messages in current msgarea (buggy?)

MsgSig [Sig]               - Set current MsgSIG.

ListMsgAreas               - List Message-areas in this SIG.

ListMsgSIGs                - List available SIGs.

PrevMsgArea                - Go to previous messagearea.

FileArea [Number]          - Go to a filearea.

Download                   - Download marked files.

MarkFile [Spec]            - Mark file(s).

DosMarkFile [Filename]     - Mark any file on the harddisk.

AddFile [Name]             - Add a file to current filearea.

NextFileArea               - Go to filearea+1.

BackFileArea               - Go to filearea-1.

LiMarkedFiles              - List marked files.

ListMarkedFiles            - Same as above

Upload [destinationpath]   - Upload files in current area (or path).

FileSIG [SIGnr]            - Set current FileSIG.

ListFileAreas              - List fileareas in current SIG.

ListFileSIGs               - List available file-SIGs.

RemoveFiles                - Un-mark files.

SearchFile [String]        - Search in current filearea.

ViewArchive [Spec]         - View archive in current area.

PrevFileArea               - Go to previous filearea.

PRM_Menu [Gfxmode]         - Set graphics-mode.

PRM_Handle [Handle]        - Set user's handle.

PRM_ScrLength [Lines]      - Set user's screen-height.

PRM_UserName [Name]        - Set user's username.

PRM_City [City]            - Set user's city.

PRM_Access [Access]        - Set user's accesslevel.

PRM_Tele [Tele]            - Set user's phone-number.

PRM_Expert [On/off]        - Toggle or set expertmode.

PRM_Zip [Zip]              - Set user's zip-code.

PRM_FSEd [number]          - Asks the user of which FS-Editor to use.

PRM_Cludges [On/off]       - Toggle or set user's msgcludge-mode.

PRM_Password [Pw]          - Set user's password.

PRM_XLate [Table]          - Set user's character-translation.

PRM_Birth [YYMMDD]         - Set user's birth-data.

PRM_Optimize [On/Off]      - Toggle or set textoptimizing

PRM_Address [address]      - Set user's address.

PRM_Protocol               - Asks a user to select a UL/DL protocol

PRM_Computer               - Asks a user to select a computer

ReturnFPL                  - Return from a standard-menu to the FPL-script.

GlbList_NS_All [Sig]       - Global-list, unsorted, of all files in Sig.

GlbList_NS_New [Sig]       - Global-list, unsorted, of new files in Sig.

GlbList_NS_Search [String] - Global-list, unsorted, of all files matching
                             string.

GlbList_NS_SearchUL [Name] - Global-list, unsorted, of all files that
                             Name has uploaded.

GlbList_NS_Unval [String]  - Global-list, unsorted, of all unvalidated
                             files.

